    • addNode

      public void addNode​(TreeNode root, java.lang.Object code, java.lang.Object letter)
      Inserts a node with the specified data into the tree. The recursive algorithm involved works as follows: 1. Checks if the current root has nothing in it and places the node in there if that is true (This is for cases where the code is longer than the actual path to an empty node, since this ia a public method and people can easily make that kind of input). 2. Checks if the code string length is less than or equal to 0 and returns if that is true. 3. Checks if the code string length is equal to 1. If it is, then the node will be stored in the left child of the root if the singular character is a "." or to the right if it is a "-". 4. Otherwise, the code string has more than one character. If the first character is a ".", then the left child will be given a new node with "nothing123" (indicating nothing in that node), and the method will call itself with this left child as the root, the code with everything but the first character as the code, and the letter which remains the same. If it is a "-", then the same thing happens except it goes to the right child instead.
      Specified by:
      addNode in interface LinkedConverterTreeInterface
      Parameters:
      root - : The actual root of the tree. During recursion, it is the current node being checked. code: the letter in Morse code. this is used to move through the tree. letter: The letter being added to the tree.
      code - the code for this particular recursive instance of addNode
      letter - the data of the new TreeNode to be added

    • fetchNode

      public java.lang.Object fetchNode​(TreeNode root, java.lang.Object code)
      Returns the data contained by a node in the tree, which is found using the specified code. The recursive algorithm for this method is as follows: 1. Checks if the root is null and returns an empty String if so. 2. Returns the data in the current root if the length of the code String is less than or equal to 0. 3. If the length of the code String is one, then the method calls itself with the left child as the root and an empty String as the code String if the character is a ".", or the same thing but with the right child as the root if the character is a "-". 4. If the length of the code String is more than one, then the method calls itself with the left or right child of the current root (depending on whether the character is a "." or a "-", as explained before) as the new root, and the code String with every character except the first one as the code String. 5. If for some reason, none of this works, then an empty String will be returned by default.
      Specified by:
      fetchNode in interface LinkedConverterTreeInterface
      Parameters:
      root - : the actual root of the tree. During recursion, this is the current node being checked. code: a String of Morse code which is used to find the desired node.
      code - the code for this particular recursive instance of fetchNode
      Returns:
      the data contained inside the node which corresponds to the code String in the tree.

    • LNRoutputTraversal

      public void LNRoutputTraversal​(TreeNode root, java.util.ArrayList list)
      Stores each element from this tree into an ArrayList in LNR order. The algorithm to do this goes as follows: 1. The method calls itself with the left child of the root as the new root if the left child of the root is not null. 2. Adds the data from the current root to the list 3. Performs step one again but with he right child.
      Specified by:
      LNRoutputTraversal in interface LinkedConverterTreeInterface
      Parameters:
      root - : The actual root of the tree. During recursion, it is the current node being checked, and added after the method is called with its left child as the root. list: The ArrayList being used to store the values in LNR order.
      list - the ArrayList that will hold the contents of the tree in LNR order
